76561198077987627,Recommended,285330,25561439,"Posted: 17 September, 2016",all,Jonathan Taylor Thomas,"It's pretty hard not to do a joke review about this game with all of the top-tier memes it gives you.However, this is a game I hold dearly. It has a place in my heart no other game can fill, and it will always be the first computer game I ever had that gave me something to show off to friends with.You see, if you got this game from a cereal box (like most of us did), you are part of the best generation to experience PC gaming.Or, who knows. Maybe you played the crap out of text-based adventures back in the day and just happened to love sugary cereal at the tender age of adulthood.It truly was a good time to get into the idea of gaming on your computer. Not because legendary, classic titles came in cereal boxes, but because everyone of the ""common genres"" of game weren't set in stone yet and plenty of new companies were making PC games that were always probing an aspect of the video game that hasn't been looked into before. Nowadays the market of new games can be separated into ""niche indie titles"", ""AAA games with PC ports"" and the rare ""well-rounded good game"". Back then... you had the Tycoon series.Ladies and gentlemen, the Tycoon series of games was probably what saved me from adolescent boredom and actually gave me something fun to do on Windows 98.Bored after school? Boot up ""Extreme Heights"" and build another coaster that manages to do 10 loops in a row.You could basically build whatever park you wanted and force dumb, oblivious NPCs to eat up whatever crap you make. The system was intricate. It was always giving you feedback for how reasonable your setup is, as well as fine-tuning over even the most menial tasks.The slow nature of the game gave the players a lot of choice and challenge. Do you spend all of your money at once for something that can either make or break the park, or build a bunch of safe, small rides that will only gradually build me money?It feels a little weird writing this review because of the fact that I never really stopped with RollerCoaster Tycoon games. It's a game I will always respect and my one hope is that it is never lost and forgotten.The nostalgia value in this game is equivalent to Sock 'Em Boppers and Lincoln Logs."
