,Recommended,285330,32729662,Posted: 24 June,all,SugarBomb,"This game is fun, if you enjoy the isometric strategy games as much as I do, but be warned; there's more to it that what you think, both positively and negatively. I highly suggest it, however, to anyone new in the Amusement park tycoon genre, as I think it'll appeal more to you guys.Let's start off with the cons. Really, I only found one because the game doesn't lag, has lasting gameplay, and other things. However, be warned; all of this doesn't matter if you don't download open RCT2. The game will crash on you, deleting all of yuor data you didn't save, and it does this frequently. I don't know if this is fixed, but I'd rather not try to find out. One other thing that may make you choose the original over this one; the scenarios in this are actually pre-built, and they have some attractions, and clear areas to put roller coasters or rides. That's about it. This game will not dissapoint you if you're into this sort of thing.Alright, time for the pros.I would have to start off with the lasting gameplay. Different rides and different coasters are unlocked through reasearch, so you'll have to spend some time not only collecting money to build rides, but spending money to research them. This is a neat little mechanic I appreciate because it makes the game last longer without an obvious barrier, since it allows you to allocate your funds in research.Another detail I noticed is how different scenarios have different coasters. You can make different scenarios in this game, albeit with a limited pallete. What does this mean? Well, it means you can't choose every single roller coaster and attraction along with every single scenery. This has it's ups and downs. On the one hand, it makes the gameplay sweeter knowing that you can't experience everything in one playthrough. On the other, though, you'll feel limited when it comes to options if you want to have everything from the start. I think you should be able to choose, but it's mainly due to sprite limitations.Last thing I would have to say is that it delivers. Yes, the graphics are pretty bad, and yes, the rotation does take some getting used to, but for a 10$ game, it's pretty solid in content. As I write this, it is 3.50; definetly worth it. If you aren't going to play it now, buy it for later.There is one final thing I have to put forward, that goes along with my previous statement; it's old. This game, even if you will enjoy it, does have it's limitations. If you want a low-budget tycoon game, then this is the game for you. It does everything it says it does for 10$ and more. If you're looking for a better rollercoaster tycoon game, though, you'll have to go planet coaster. Planet coaster does everything mention above without crashing, with better controls, more availability, and the fact the camera is 3d makes it better for everyone and more modern. The graphics are great, but for all of that, you'll have to pay over a couple of more bucks. So while RCT2 game has more content, it has less overall than Planet Coaster.Well, that's all I had to say. If you are new, definetly get this game. If you are looking for a game to play meanwhile, get the game. In fact, there is barely any reason *not* to get the game. Just don't forget to download OpenRCT2 for the crashed :)"
