76561198374560647,Recommended,285330,35430203,Posted: 2 October,all,Um Jammer Chelle,"RollerCoaster Tycoon was the first PC game I ever played. I spent countless hours just playing the first two scenarios alone. RollerCoaster Tycoon 2 however, was a game I never played until I bought it a couple months ago. It's safe to say that I love it as much as the original. Don't let my playtime fool you, I've put in at least 48 hours into it through ""OpenRCT2."" I highly recommend you play it through OpenRCT2, as it adds a bunch of cool features that weren't in the original game such as cheats and multiplayer. Anyways, I'll try and base my review on the original product alone. If you've ever played the original RCT, then it's basically more of that. It builds upon the foundation of the original game by adding more rides, scenarios, scenery, and other things. Your goal is to build a successful theme park in one of the various scenarios. You must build rides that entice guests to spend their hard earned cash. You also have to build shops, stalls, and bathrooms so that your guests can keep their needs high and stay in the park longer. You can build a variety of rides and add a variety of theming around them, but the most involved rides are the roller coasters. You can build them yourself, or choose from a variety of prebuilt coasters. The roller coaster building is probably my favourite part of the game. You can build the best rollercoaster ever, (and find out guests won't ride it because it's too intense) or you can build death traps that fly off the rails and kill your guests. The only downside is that you can't ride them in first person due to technical limitations of the time. However, you can watch guests ride them. Throw in some staff management, path management, and budgeting, and you've pretty much covered most of the gameplay. My biggest gripe with the game is probably the lack of ""free building maps."" The scenarios are cool, but there aren't as many open maps like there was in the first game. Another problem I have is how there aren't any maps with both a park entry fee and ride fees. This seems rather odd as most real life parks operate with both admission prices and ride prices. Finally there is no fast forward button in the base game. (OpenRCT2 adds some) This can make it a bit dull when you're waiting for enough income to build your next idea. The graphics have aged well. They have an art style that is cheerful and enjoying to look at. My only complaint with them is probably the isometric view. It adds some struggle to finding a good position for the camera to see things. Thankfully the see-through rides and scenery options exist to compensate for the lack of full camera control. I also love the sound mixing. The park is completely silent until you start adding rides with music. It really adds to the atmosphere of your park. One feature I forgot to mention earlier is the customization. It's top notch. From theming your park, to naming your rides, it's great. You can even rename the guests.Here's a list of the pros and cons for me.Pros:-Fantastic gameplay-Interesting scenarios-Charming graphics-Variety of rides-The roller coaster building-The customization-Hours upon hours of replayabilityCons:-Not as many open maps as RCT-Isometric view can be a bit confusing sometimes-Can't ride roller coasters-Not being able to charge for both rides and admission at the same time (OpenRCT2 fixes this)-No fast forward button (OpenRCT2 fixes this)In conclusion, RollerCoaster Tycoon 2 is one of the best tycoon games out there. It’s basically nothing but improvements over the original. If you're looking for a theme park management game, it doesn't get much better than this."
